<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="145" pageId="13" pageNumber="144" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="144">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="145" pageId="13" pageNumber="144">
Together with 
<taxonomicName lsidName="jamaicensis" pageId="13" pageNumber="144" rank="species" species="jamaicensis">jamaicensis</taxonomicName>
, Schaus (1901) originally placed this species in the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Heterusia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterusia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Heterusia</taxonomicName>
. It was then ranked down as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="mortipax" pageId="13" pageNumber="144" rank="species" species="mortipax">mortipax</taxonomicName>
by Parsons et 
<pageBreakToken pageId="14" pageNumber="145" start="start">al</pageBreakToken>
. (1999). The major characteristic of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="acothysta" pageId="14" pageNumber="145" rank="species" species="acothysta">acothysta</taxonomicName>
is the reduction of the white transversal band (found both in 
<taxonomicName lsidName="mortipax" pageId="14" pageNumber="145" rank="species" species="mortipax">mortipax</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName lsidName="jamaicensis" pageId="14" pageNumber="145" rank="species" species="jamaicensis">jamaicensis</taxonomicName>
) to a smaller blotch that reaches about half the area found in 
<taxonomicName lsidName="mortipax" pageId="14" pageNumber="145" rank="species" species="mortipax">mortipax</taxonomicName>
. As in 
<taxonomicName lsidName="jamaicensis" pageId="14" pageNumber="145" rank="species" species="jamaicensis">jamaicensis</taxonomicName>
, further evidence from barcoding is desirable for the consolidation of the species status.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="145" type="distribution">
